“LIBERALS have to stand up for LIBERAL principles.” - Bill Maher, agreeing with me on this exact issue. If I can speak for about 4 sentences without being shamed as a racist or Islamophobe, when we as conservatives say that “we don’t care where immigrants come from, but they HAVE to be ready to accept western principles,” this is what we mean. The open-borders European left has perpetuated the lie that all cultures are created equal, that people from outside the west are inherently righteous, and that radical Islam makes up a tiny portion of the global Muslim population (the last one is statistically untrue). The open-borders left in America believes much of the same. But, all of these beliefs are blatantly wrong. The chaos, crime, rape, and murder that the migrant crisis has brought to Europe is a shining example of the need for a merit-based immigration system AND strict border security here in the US, and any true champion of women’s rights, #feminism, #MeToo, or “REAL Muslims” would agree.

@c.onsumerism unless I expressly call Obama a communist or AOC a Maoist, I am not perpetuating this so called meme. “Left” and “right,” are extremely broad labels with pretty much hundreds of different ideologies on varying sections of their respective sides of the spectrum. It’s not my fault that people misidentify other people’s ideologies, and even with ur spectrum that could still happen (IE aye yo Ron Paul is an ANARCHIST). Right and left are broad denominations regardless of where the line is drawn. Just because someone is “right” or “left” doesn’t automatically mean they specifically adhere to one righting or leftwing ideology, it just describes the general nature of their beliefs. You’re right that the ideas of right and left are pretty exclusive to the US, but again, considering the fact this page is dedicated to current American politics, I use the definitions that we accept here in America. Semantics doesn’t make discourse harder unless you make a big deal out of them instead of the ideas being presented, which is what you’re doing. It frankly doesn’t matter what you refer to yourself as, and regardless there will always be people who are confused by the labels, what matters are the ideas being presented.

@daos.day by actively misusing labels that originate from academia in and thus alienating them from their established meaning, you are feeding into wave of people misusing and mislabelling these terms Lol this is undeniable. Semantics make discourse harder when the semantics attached to one side of the discussion are completely unreasonable and lazy lmao and saying that people will always be confused isn’t fixing the semantics issues that prevent us from taking part in more discourse

@c.onsumerism idk if u realize it or not but at the same time that u make the definition of left more specific, u also make the definition of right way more broad, general, and vague in the process. If you make the left onto an extremely small and exclusive group, you in turn make the definition of right totally ambiguous. But regardless, right and left alone are completely meaningless. They’re just labels. When you’re preaching to a crowd you obviously can use them, but when you’re actually having political discourse what matters are the ideas being talked about, not the denominations of the people talking about them. “I support Medicare for all.” “I don’t.” “I support the nationalization of industry.” “I don’t.” This is the discourse taking place, the labels only become a problem if you’re unwilling to listen to the actual ideas being presented.

(cont.): “Radical Islam” does not just refer to terrorists. Terrorists are the extremely small portion of radical Muslims who act on these beliefs, but one has to understand that they are held by far more people than just the terrorists. We misleadingly differentiate the Islamic world into simply a.) the terrorists and dictators and b.) everyone else, who must automatically love the west and be on our side. Both of these sides exist, but this outlook on the situation is simply delusional. Here’s a telling statistic that demonstrates the true magnitude of radicalism in the Muslim world: per Pew, 99% of the population of Afghanistan supports the forced implementation of Sharia law. This is not some tiny minority. None of this is to say that there aren’t moderate Muslims who are willing to accept western principles such as free speech and freedom of religion- but how is the west doing at making sure the migrants/immigrants it lets in are such moderates? Terribly- following the cartoonist incident a few years back, polling found that 78% of British Muslims want cartoonists of Muhammad to be criminally prosecuted. This is dangerous. We HAVE to create an immigration policy that is rooted in reality, not intersectionality. We have to ensure that those who we let in are willing to accept western culture, and, if we can’t properly make that determination, we need to halt immigration from these places until we figure out how to.

@thiccydaniel I don’t understand how literally an argument that took up 50-60% of ur original comment is me jumping around.  I’m extremely careful not to generalize, which is why I always identify radical Islam, not just Islam, as the problem, and why I always acknowledge that there are moderate Muslims and that they shouldn’t be banned from immigrating. The point of citing these statistics is to prevent generalization, so that I’m not just saying “yo look all Muslims are radicals.” Regardless of a Muslim’s interpretation of Sharia, the belief that their religious law should be implemented as the legal law of their country is radical. End of story. This also applies to any Christian or Jewish theocrat that believes that Biblical law should be imposed, through the force of government, on their fellow citizens. This is not the only question Pew has asked though, there have been other polls done asking questions such as should cartoonists of Muhammad be prosecuted (I also cited that), do you have positive or mixed feelings about Bin Laden, and are honor killings of women sometimes justified. And the reason, I should note, that I demonstrate that radical Islam is a far bigger problem among populations than we believe it to be (im not just trying to demonize and generalize all of them like you claim) is because it is impossible for us to create effective policy regarding the issue if we can’t first acknowledge the true scope of the problem. The problem isn’t going to ever be fixed if we maintain the delusional belief that radical Islam is this tiny, obscure, irrelevant sector of the people that follow the religion.
